TY  - JOUR
T1  - Market reaction to the formation of one-bank holding companies and the 1970 Bank Holding Company Act Amendment
AU  - Billingsley, Randall S.
AU  - Lamy, Robert E.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 8
IS  - 1
SP  - 21
EP  - 33
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/03/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(84)80022-9
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426684800229
AB  - Recent research by Martin and Keown (1981) published in this journal suggests that the formation of one-bank holding companies (OBHCs) is met by a positive market reaction but prompts no significant change in the process generating returns for such firms' common stock. This study investigates these same issues in light of the demonstrably important influence of the regulatory change which occurred during the period analyzed by Martin and Keown, i.e., the 1970 Amendment to the Bank Holding Company Act. Analysis provides evidence that OBHC formation prompted both a market reaction and a significant change in the return generating process of affected banks. Furthermore, this study suggests that the 1970 Bank Holding Company Act Amendment itself significantly affected the return generating process of OBHCs. This study thus attempts to provide investors, security analysts, and regulators with additional insight into the impacts of OBHC formation and the 1970 Amendment.
